The second is that we wing it too much.

We don't build reliable processes that are teachable, repeatable, and reportable. Leaving the individual to figure out how to organize, prioritize, and report on their work.

Which causes reliance on the individual over the team.

The first is that many folks believe you need to have a large following or be highly experienced in a given area to succeed in DevRel.

This couldn't be further from the truth. You bring value by building up context about the company and community and sharing it with others.

So how does this related to advocacy and devrel in general, you ask?

Well, it manifests in two very distinct ways.

One of the most significant issues developer advocacy or DevRel in general faces is keystone-ing.

A keystone is that wedge-shaped block in an archway that all the other blocks depend on. If it were to be removed, the whole structure would crumble.

Taking millions or more can happen in seconds, and that's never really been possible at this scale before.

This is why we can't just compare scams in web3 to scams happening in fiat currencies.
With web3 and crypto, the game is entirely different. There is so much less to work around to complete a scam. Scammers can scale up their efforts which increases the number of marks they can take.
Because of this, scammers and con artists have to get highly creative and invest a lot of effort to pull off their schemes.
Because fiat currencies are regulated, and insured companies invest in ways to prevent fraud and theft, and in the year 2022, most banks offer fraud protection and will reimburse what you lose.

The ease with which you can scam people in crypto means you need fewer resources than running traditional scams.

There are entire YT channels dedicated to "owning" scammers, but the vital thing to note about the scams attempted in those videos is time-to-complete.

The reason it's crucial to address the scam issues web3 currently faces boils down to scale.

Just like companies, crime organizations also have a limit to their resources.

You might laugh at the idea of scammers being organized, but I assure you, they are.
@ThreeBrewMates @ryanirilli @RobertTalada Because there is no protection which is why it's not the same. If it were the same there would be people trying to take advantage. https://t.co/Neh3SPsYUd

@ThreeBrewMates @ryanirilli @RobertTalada bank issue, credit card not working, need help, bank of America, visa, issues

@ThreeBrewMates @ryanirilli @RobertTalada Businesses can look legitimate. NFT drops can look legitimate. The difference is if you get taken from a company that scams you, you at least have some protection and/or recourse. In crypto, you do not.

Therefore they aren't even close to the same thing.

I have no experience working with Hasura outside of experimentation, so I can't speak to using it for managing your data. Still, Nhost does a great job of pulling everything together, and I'm interested to see where the platform goes.

The onboarding process was straightforward, and I really did have an app set up and deployed in minutes. Granted, it didn't really do much, but I had a front-end (from their templates) and all the infra I needed to start working on a project immediately.
You also get serverless functions that all get deployed together for you, so you don't have to worry about managing multiple deployment processes.

Most interesting is that your data, storage, and auth come from Hasura. Which is an exciting break from the usual we see from platforms that manage data.

What's neat is you can work with Hasura to make changes, and Nhost will handle the migration/deployment for you.

Nhost is a managed infrastructure platform that takes bits of everything and puts them together into one location for you. I dig that.

Essentially you get a DB, GraphQL API, Functions, Auth, and Storage for your application. 👍🏻

I spent the next four months getting the same basic training as Marines.

After release, I was back home with my father and on the verge of turning 18, so I left again, except this time I went alone and hitchhiked back to NJ.

[7/7]

I spent two months in juvy before being sent to VA for the car theft charges. I spent another two months there before being sentenced to a four-month juvenile boot camp.

[6/7]

This not being my first rodeo with the cops. I said nothing and denied everything. My one other friend did as well, but the other one told the police everything.

Luckily we didn't exactly stop to get the names of the places we had visited, so there wasn't much to go on.

[5/7]

A cop saw it and pulled up on us in the gas station parking lot for the traffic stop but ended up arresting us all for being in the stolen vehicle.

I was brought to the juvenile detention center for processing.

[4/7]

The goal was to take the weed back to the east coast (except to NJ, where I grew up) and sell it and then just continue to run weed from TX to NJ.

However, while going to the store for cigarettes, my friend accidentally turned the wrong way down a one-way street.

[3/7]

We made it from the Atlantic ocean to Witchita Falls, TX.

We were on our way to see one of my friend's cousins who would trade us a bunch of weed for some items we had procured *definitely legally* along the way there.

[2/7]

I had just turned 17 yrs old and lived with my abusive father in VA. I stole a car (from a dealership) with two friends to get away from him, and we embarked on a cross-country road trip.

What would it be like if you could do this for codebases? 

Imagine if all files were flat, no actual folders or organization, only virtual.

There could be a default config, and each person could override it individually to suit their workflows. It could be interesting!

Notion's cascading permissions and flexible references make it easy to maintain a pretty flat file structure and then logically group documents in other places to accommodate everyone.

Now I create all documents at the root of that space and use other pages to organize them.

Something I've been thinking about a lot is dynamic file structures. The more I get into @NotionHQ, I run into situations where I have to decide who to accommodate when I create a file somewhere.

Then it hit me that I didn't have to do that at all.

Invest in your community for real.
A very popular crypto wallet has a single blog post about protecting your crypto investments. It's essentially 8 bullet points, with the most notable being "Take training to become security-aware."
Almost every web3 site I've been to has no content about protecting yourself from the issues you might encounter using cryptocurrencies.

VCs see an emerging industry and are already pumping billions into it. Startups are popping up every day for everything you can think of too.

Interestingly enough, though, no one seems to be concerned with educating anyone about how to safely navigate crypto and web3.

If this was someone else who lost an NFT and it didn't make so much noise, there is a good chance opensea would do nothing.

I see artists fighting to get stolen work taken down daily and people being taken for everything they have, but it's not apes, so no help comes.

For the record, I'm trying to call them out, it sucks that they got caught up and I see nothing wrong with opensea trying to help with stolen NFTs.

My point is that opensea chose to do that, but they don't HAVE to.

This is why it is inevitable no matter what you say about crypto or web3. It's here. It's helping a lot of folks.

Yet, it's also harming a lot of folks.  Scams and hacks are rampant and even the most avid crypto users are susceptible to being taken.

https://t.co/st0yAZuuYN
There are many folks worldwide that need access to some form of currency right now, not in five or ten years when the dust settles.

I think about the web3/crypto space a lot, and the biggest realization I've had is that having the ability to wait and see what happens with it is a privilege.

Not everyone can afford to "wait and see" what happens before investing more in it.

If you'd like to learn more about individualized training, you can see all the programs currently offered here:
https://t.co/a3TXgXgRC0.

If you'd like to learn more about team workshops, you can see all the labs currently offered here:
https://t.co/tavXARV3Rp.
If you're curious about how Forthright can help your company with its DX challenges, you can learn more here: https://t.co/HmAVHFTqGM.

I'll also be putting on a free developer experience conference (DX Conf) this fall, as well as starting a new DX-focused community discord server where I hope we can all learn together.

I'm incredibly excited about the future of Forthright and our community!

In the spirit of that sentiment, for every team workshop or individualized training I take on through Forthright, I'll provide one to folks from marginalized communities for free. I'll be working with some organizations shortly, so stay tuned for more info!

It's nice to want to help folks, but so far, I've only spoken about things you have to pay for, which doesn't seem very helpful to the community at large.

We push developer experience forward together, not alone, not in small closed-off groups, together.

My goal is to help improve DX at every level:

- I want to help companies through advising and services
- I want to help teams through collaborative training
- I want to help individuals through individualized training
Forthright will focus on helping companies build out and strengthen their developer experience strategies and educating through workshops and individualized training.
Alright, back to the mission. How will I help companies, teams, and individuals create better experiences?

But I still feel like there is more I can do. I want to empower so many people in the developer experience community, and consulting seems to be the correct answer when I think about how to have the most significant impact.

Like the communities you help every day, DX is itself a community. I want to help our community grow and thrive.

I've put out content that I hope has helped others, I've spoken with and mentored many incredible people, and I've helped shape DX at a few companies.

Forthright's mission is to help companies, teams, and individuals create better developer experiences.

Today, I'd like to share what that means to me and how I plan to bring that mission to life. 🧵

"An event or occurrence within a company's ecosystem…

This is largely why I believe that:

1) DevRel is not the right umbrella. DX is.

2) Developer Experience is often way too narrowly scoped.

An event or occurrence can happen within a company's ecosystem without a developer interacting with another person.

There doesn't have to be a relationship to have an experience, but there need to be positive experiences to have a relationship.

Let's tighten the lens a bit more and add the context of a company.

"An event or occurrence within a company's ecosystem that leaves an impression on a developer"

That is what DX is. ☝🏻☝🏻☝🏻

Now, let's frame this in terms of developers:

"An event or occurrence that leaves an impression on a developer."

To start the conversation, I'd like to reference one of the definitions of the word "experience" found in the dictionary.

"An event or occurrence that leaves an impression on someone." 🤔 https://t.co/LbVkJ8ZOmW

@tanoaksam To me developer relations is about building internal and external relationships to help improve developer experience and foster healthy relationships between company and community.
It's not going to get better until we make it better. 💜

Our function is new and new things need clear terminology and definitions. 

Imagine if the content you created to describe an API or product used one term to define so many things. 🤔
Unpopular opinion: using the term "DevRel" to represent the entirety of what Developer Experience has become as a function is doing insurmountable damage to the field.

This leaves us having to either:

- move away from initiatives that drive internal impact

- adopt one department's goals as our own to get the trust we need (move DevRel under Marketing, Product, Engineering, etc)

- provide constant positive qualitative data for proof of impact
Because DX/DevRel/Community stuff is new, often, our metrics aren't trusted by other departments and execs in the company to represent the impact we say is associated with them.

Try not to get so caught up in showing the impact you're creating that you don't provide enough context to get the buy-in you need when you want to scale an initiative or team.

This situation really stems from DevRel not having trusted metrics that represent our impact.

When you don't share the pain points you're experiencing, you paint the picture that the initiative is running smoothly.

When things appear to be running smoothly and delivering value, it can be hard to convince people that you need help to scale that initiative.

An interesting problem I've observed with DevRel is that because we often have to prove impact on things we do, we hesitate to share any of the challenges and only focus on the wins to prevent losing buy-in.

This can inadvertently affect your ability to scale those initiatives!

@oliverjumpertz @PeterPanYes @dabit3 While the target audience is developer advocates, this process is helpful in tech leads, staff, and principal engineers as well!

I know of someone using this framework to drive a significant initiative right now.

One of the things that makes DevRel so valuable is our ability to connect business benefits to developer pain points, so developers don't have to do it themselves.

The benefits may be there, but if developers can't see how it solves their problems, they won't care.

A lot of marketing terminology is focused on the business benefits, which makes sense because it's businesses that eventually pay for the thing being marketed.

However, developers often won't take the time to dig through the business benefits to see how it solves their problems.

Maybe we've been burned too many times by top-down technology choices that affected our quality of life, or perhaps the messaging doesn't really resonate with our experience. 

Regardless we tend to tune out when words like innovation appear.

I've thought a lot about why developers distrust traditional marketing, and I've essentially decided it's because they tend to believe their problems are separate from business concerns. Therefore, only other developers could understand what they need. 🧵

Anyway, it's already hard enough for folks to get into content creation (especially video) and devrel, but I fear the gap will only worsen in the future.

An example of this in real life is watching old movies. 

Unless you have some sort of emotional connection or it's a rare movie that can stand the test of time, they can be pretty unbearable to watch.

Don't get me wrong, those videos had both great content and great filmmaking, but I feel like that's part of the issue.

It means soon, the quality of content might not be enough to stand out.

Many folks say you don't need excellent equipment to be successful with video content, and I think it's true for right now, but that won't hold up for long.

As video quality increases (GitHub Universe), so do people's expectations of what quality is.
One of my biggest concerns about the emergence of video as the new way of delivering content is that as the quality of video increases, so does the barrier to entry to create video content.

Developers should definitely be educated about things like testing, best practices, awareness of pre-existing code, but I feel they should be educated about them outside of PRs.

@careecodes If it's about styling, best practices, code coverage, then there might not be enough guardrails in place.

If it's about making sure code is reused, patterns are followed, abstractions are sound, etc. Then it feels like the wrong person is responsible for that PR.

@careecodes If a dev feels like they are taking on all the burden, they don't trust the process.

If leaders feel like they need to check every PR to ensure the system will not be negatively impacted, they don't trust the current process.

@GregWildSmith I prefer to put as many guardrails in place as possible to prevent something bad from happening and have solid processes in place for when it inevitably does.

It feels wrong to optimize for the least likely situation (outside of particular cases).

This problem compounds for every new client you introduce as well!

Would you prefer to do that ETL work one time on the server or repeatedly on the client?

GraphQL solves many problems, but I'm especially giddy about not having to make every client developer a data engineer.

In her recent article, @shrutikapoor08 details the main reasons they adopted GraphQL at PayPal, and the first three are all related to client-side ETL.

https://t.co/Z7M8u7gB4Q

When we leave the work of aggregating and transforming data into a format usable by a client application, we're making them do ETL.

They have to extract the data from multiple endpoints, transform it into a data set usable by the application, and then load it into the UI.

It's funny how we often ask front-end developers to also be data engineers without even meaning to.

You might have heard the acronym "ETL" before. ETL stands for extract, transform, and load. It's a process data engineers use to change large sets of data.

This one image sums up why I chose #GraphQL for @MLS all the way back in 2017.

We were revamping one of the most trafficked web properties, and once I started collaborating with the design team, I could immediately see the complexity of the client. 🧵 https://t.co/CTc5rEfDT4
